{
  "id": "ternary",
  "title": "JS Ternary",
  "group": "JS Conditions",
  "content": [
    { "type": "h1", "text": "JavaScript Ternary Operator" },
    { "type": "p", "text": "The ternary operator is the only JavaScript operator that takes three operands. It provides a concise way to write simple if/else statements in a single line. The syntax is: condition ? expressionIfTrue : expressionIfFalse." },

    { "type": "h2", "text": "Basic Syntax" },
    { "type": "p", "text": "The ternary operator evaluates a condition. If the condition is true, it returns the first expression. If false, it returns the second expression." },
    { "type": "example", "title": "Basic Ternary", "code": [
      "let age = 20;",
      "let status = age >= 18 ? \"Adult\" : \"Minor\";",
      "console.log(status); // \"Adult\"",
      "",
      "let hour = 14;",
      "let greeting = hour < 12 ? \"Good morning\" : \"Good afternoon\";",
      "console.log(greeting); // \"Good afternoon\"",
      "",
      "let isRaining = true;",
      "console.log(isRaining ? \"Bring umbrella\" : \"Enjoy the sun\");",
      "// \"Bring umbrella\""
    ]},

    { "type": "h2", "text": "Ternary vs if/else" },
    { "type": "p", "text": "The ternary operator is best for simple assignments and return values. Use if/else for complex logic, side effects, or multiple statements." },
    { "type": "example", "title": "Comparing Ternary and if/else", "code": [
      "let score = 85;",
      "",
      "// Using if/else (4 lines)",
      "let result1;",
      "if (score >= 60) {",
      "  result1 = \"Pass\";",
      "} else {",
      "  result1 = \"Fail\";",
      "}",
      "console.log(result1); // \"Pass\"",
      "",
      "// Using ternary (1 line)",
      "let result2 = score >= 60 ? \"Pass\" : \"Fail\";",
      "console.log(result2); // \"Pass\"",
      "",
      "// Ternary in template literals",
      "let items = 5;",
      "console.log(`You have ${items} item${items === 1 ? \"\" : \"s\"}`);",
      "// \"You have 5 items\""
    ]},

    { "type": "h2", "text": "Nested Ternary" },
    { "type": "p", "text": "You can nest ternary operators to handle multiple conditions. However, deeply nested ternaries can be hard to read â€” use sparingly and consider if/else for complex cases." },
    { "type": "example", "title": "Nested Ternary", "code": [
      "let score = 75;",
      "",
      "// Nested ternary (use with caution)",
      "let grade = score >= 90 ? \"A\"",
      "           : score >= 80 ? \"B\"",
      "           : score >= 70 ? \"C\"",
      "           : score >= 60 ? \"D\"",
      "           : \"F\";",
      "",
      "console.log(grade); // \"C\"",
      "",
      "// Another example",
      "let num = 0;",
      "let sign = num > 0 ? \"positive\"",
      "          : num < 0 ? \"negative\"",
      "          : \"zero\";",
      "console.log(sign); // \"zero\""
    ]},

    { "type": "h2", "text": "Using Ternary in Assignments" },
    { "type": "p", "text": "Ternary operators are particularly useful when assigning values based on conditions, setting function arguments, or building strings dynamically." },
    { "type": "example", "title": "Practical Ternary Uses", "code": [
      "// Dynamic assignment",
      "let isLoggedIn = true;",
      "let message = `Welcome ${isLoggedIn ? \"back\" : \"guest\"}!`;",
      "console.log(message); // \"Welcome back!\"",
      "",
      "// Function argument",
      "let darkMode = true;",
      "let bgColor = darkMode ? \"#333\" : \"#fff\";",
      "console.log(bgColor); // \"#333\"",
      "",
      "// Conditional method call",
      "let arr = [3, 1, 4, 1, 5];",
      "let sorted = true;",
      "let output = sorted ? arr.sort((a, b) => a - b) : arr;",
      "console.log(output); // [1, 1, 3, 4, 5]",
      "",
      "// Ternary for null checks",
      "let user = { name: \"Alice\" };",
      "let displayName = user ? user.name : \"Anonymous\";",
      "console.log(displayName); // \"Alice\""
    ]},

    { "type": "h2", "text": "When NOT to Use Ternary" },
    { "type": "p", "text": "Avoid ternary when you need multiple statements, side effects, or complex branching logic. If you struggle to read a ternary at a glance, use if/else instead." },
    { "type": "example", "title": "When to Prefer if/else", "code": [
      "let action = \"save\";",
      "",
      "// BAD: ternary with side effects",
      "// action === \"save\" ? saveData() : deleteData(); // avoid this",
      "",
      "// GOOD: use if/else for side effects",
      "if (action === \"save\") {",
      "  console.log(\"Saving data...\");",
      "  // Additional save logic here",
      "} else {",
      "  console.log(\"Deleting data...\");",
      "  // Additional delete logic here",
      "}",
      "",
      "// GOOD: ternary for simple values",
      "let label = action === \"save\" ? \"Save\" : \"Delete\";",
      "console.log(label); // \"Save\""
    ]},

    { "type": "note", "text": "Nested ternary operators should be formatted with each condition on its own line for readability. If the ternary has more than 2 levels of nesting, refactor to if/else or a lookup object." },

    { "type": "exercise", "question": "What does the expression true ? \"yes\" : \"no\" return?", "options": ["true", "\"yes\"", "\"no\"", "undefined"], "answer": 1 }
  ]
}
